"""
mkt-context Layer — Exodus chapters 28–29
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-exodus-28-29-fill.py

Key historical/ANE context decisions:
- Ch 28: Egyptian and Mesopotamian priestly vestment traditions as comparanda; the ephod's
  function as oracular device (attested in Judg 8:27; 1 Sam 23:9); Urim and Thummim as
  binary lots (1 Sam 14:41 LXX); twelve breastpiece stones with debated identifications
  (ancient gem catalogues in Egyptian and Mesopotamian texts); the bells (pa'amonim) as
  apotropaic threshold-crossing devices common in ANE religious contexts.
- Ch 29: Seven-day ordination mirrors ANE royal investiture patterns; blood on ear/thumb/toe
  as whole-body consecration attested across the ANE; 'filling of the hands' (male' yad)
  = the Akkadian idiom qatam malu for investiture with office; the tamid (daily offering)
  parallels Mesopotamian temple daily-offering programs; re'ach nicho'ach formula appears
  in Ugaritic and Babylonian texts; the covenant-dwelling formula (v.43-46) as the
  theological climax of the entire tabernacle instruction block (chs.25-29).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS_CONTEXT = {
  "28": {
    "1": "<p><b>Then bring near to you Aaron your brother, and his sons with him, from among the people of Israel, to serve me as priests — Aaron, Nadab, and Abihu, Eleazar and Ithamar:</b> The four sons of Aaron are named in order of birth; Nadab and Abihu are the eldest, who will die in Lev 10 for offering unauthorized fire before YHWH. The priestly office is hereditary — chosen from within a specific clan (the Kohathite branch of Levi). Egyptian and Mesopotamian priesthoods were similarly hereditary in many cases; the Babylonian 'ashipu' (exorcist-priest) office passed from father to son, as did Egyptian temple priesthoods in particular sanctuary families. The Israelite priestly genealogy creates an institutional continuity secured by bloodline.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>And you shall make holy garments (bigdei qodesh) for Aaron your brother, for glory and for beauty (l'khavod ul'tifaret):</b> Bigdei qodesh = holy garments (garments that belong to the holy sphere); the two stated purposes — kavod (glory/weight) and tifaret (beauty/splendor) — are the same aesthetic categories used throughout the tabernacle's design. Egyptian priests wore specific garments according to rank and function: ordinary priests wore white linen; the sem-priest (funerary officiant) wore a distinctive spotted leopard skin; the high priest of Ptah at Memphis wore elaborate vestments. The aesthetic of priestly vestments in Egypt and Israel shared the principle that the deity's representative must dress in a manner befitting the deity's glory.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>You shall speak to all the skillful, whom I have filled with a spirit of skill (ruach chakhmah), that they make Aaron's garments to consecrate him for my priesthood:</b> The same Spirit-gift of craftsmanship (ruach chakhmah = spirit of wisdom/skill) that qualified Bezalel for tabernacle construction (31:3) qualifies the craftsmen for the vestments. The priestly garments require the same quality of inspired craftsmanship as the tabernacle structure itself; the priest's clothing is as much a sacred artifact as the ark or the menorah. The ruach chakhmah as a specialist divine endowment for technical skill is a broader concept than we often recognize — it encompasses material and aesthetic intelligence as a form of divine wisdom.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>These are the garments that they shall make: a breastpiece, an ephod, a robe, a coat of checkered work, a turban, and a sash:</b> The six primary vestments listed in descending order from most sacred (breastpiece + ephod) to functional (tunic, turban, sash). The inventory of priestly vestments has precise parallels in ANE priestly investiture lists. Ugaritic texts describe the garments of the god Baal and the priestly vestments in the Baal Cycle; Mesopotamian temple texts list the garments put on divine statues during rituals. The six-item vestment list creates a complete coverage of the priest's body from head (turban) to foot (tunic and sash).</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>They shall receive gold, blue and purple and scarlet yarns, and fine twined linen:</b> The four colors of the tabernacle's inner curtains (gold thread, blue t'khelet, purple argaman, scarlet tola'at shani, and fine linen shesh) are the same four colors used throughout the high-priestly garments. The priest dresses in the same palette as the tabernacle he serves in — the high priest becomes a walking embodiment of the sacred space. T'khelet blue was derived from the hilazon snail (a Mediterranean coastal mollusk, probably Murex trunculus); the dye was enormously expensive and its use was restricted to royalty and high-status religious contexts throughout the ancient Mediterranean world.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>And they shall make the ephod of gold, of blue and purple and scarlet yarns, and of fine twined linen, skillfully worked:</b> The ephod (possibly from Egyptian hbt = a specific garment) is the most enigmatic of the priestly vestments; its exact form is debated. It was worn over the robe and served as the mounting for the breastpiece via gold chains and rings. In later Israelite history, the ephod was used as an oracular device (Judg 8:27; 17:5; 1 Sam 23:9-12; 30:7-8) — Gideon made a golden ephod that became a cult object. The priestly ephod here is distinguished from the linen ephod worn by non-Aaronic priests (1 Sam 2:18; 2 Sam 6:14) and from the idol-form ephod of Judg 17-18.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>It shall have two shoulder pieces attached to its two edges, so that it may be joined together:</b> The two shoulder-pieces (sh'tei k'tefot = two shoulders) are the structural elements to which the onyx stones bearing the tribal names will be attached (v.9-12). The 'shoulder' of a garment is the structural pivot; carrying the names of the tribes on his shoulders means the high priest literally bears Israel when he enters the divine presence. The shoulder-carrying imagery is employed throughout the Bible for bearing responsibility and identity (Isa 9:6 — 'the government shall be on his shoulder'; 22:22 — 'the key of the house of David on his shoulder').</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>And the skillfully woven band on it shall be of the same workmanship and material, of gold, blue and purple and scarlet yarns, and fine twined linen:</b> The 'artistically woven waistband' (cheshev ha-ephodo) is integral to the ephod — woven of the same materials, not merely tied on. The technical term cheshev (waistband/belt of the ephod) is related to the verb chashav (to think/devise/weave patterns), connecting the artisanal skill to the conceptual intelligence of the designer.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>You shall take two onyx stones (shoham) and engrave on them the names of the sons of Israel:</b> Shoham is identified as onyx in most translations, but the exact stone is debated — it may be sardius, beryl, or another precious stone. The engraving of names on precious stones was practiced in Egypt and Mesopotamia; Egyptian signet rings and Mesopotamian cylinder seals bore carved inscriptions and names. The names of the twelve tribes engraved on the shoulder stones create a permanent, durable record of YHWH's covenant people — the priest carries the covenant community into the divine presence in stone.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>Six of their names on the one stone, and the names of the remaining six on the other stone, in the order of their birth:</b> The division of twelve names into two groups of six mirrors the spatial organization of the twelve tribes (six on each side) and the twelve stones of the breastpiece (three rows of four). The 'order of their birth' (k'toldotam = according to their generations/births) uses the toledot vocabulary that structures the entire book of Genesis — the twelve tribal names organized by genealogical sequence connect the tabernacle to the Abrahamic covenant promise.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>As a jeweler engraves signets (pit'chei chotam), so shall you engrave the two stones with the names of the sons of Israel:</b> Chotam = seal/signet (the personal identification seal worn as a ring or pendant, used to authenticate documents); pit'chei chotam = engravings of a seal. The tribal names engraved like signet-seals mean the twelve tribes are YHWH's authenticated, sealed possession — their names are engraved by the authority of the divine presence. Egyptian and Babylonian seals were engraved with names, titles, and divine symbols; the seal was the most personal and legally binding identification instrument in the ancient world. YHWH's 'sealed' tribes parallels the sealing language of Eph 1:13 and Rev 7:3-8.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>And you shall set the two stones on the shoulder pieces of the ephod, as stones of remembrance (avnei zikaron) for the sons of Israel. And Aaron shall bear their names before YHWH on his two shoulders for remembrance:</b> Avnei zikaron = stones of remembrance (from zakar = to remember); the stones' purpose is to bring the tribes 'to remembrance' (l'zikaron) before YHWH. The priestly intercession built into the vestments is architectural: Aaron cannot enter the divine presence without physically carrying the twelve tribes on his shoulders. The concept of 'remembrance before YHWH' is the theological engine of Israelite prayer — asking YHWH to 'remember' is asking YHWH to act on behalf of the one remembered (cf. Gen 8:1 — 'God remembered Noah').</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>You shall make settings of gold filigree (mishb'tzot zahav):</b> Mishbetzot = gold filigree settings (from the root shavatz = to work in interweaved/checker pattern); the gold settings are the mounting frames for the onyx shoulder stones. Ancient Egyptian and Mesopotamian jewelry techniques included sophisticated stone-setting methods; the Tell el-Ajjul and Ugaritic gold jewelry assemblages (from the Late Bronze Age = the likely period of the Exodus) demonstrate the level of goldsmithing skill available in the region.</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>And two chains of pure gold, twisted like cords (avotot); and you shall attach the corded chains to the settings:</b> Avotot = twisted/braided (from avat = to twist); the twisted-cord gold chains that connect the shoulder settings to the breastpiece rings. The description of the connecting chains as twisted/braided is technically specific — twisted cord is stronger than a flat chain. The structural engineering of the vestments (how the breastpiece stays in place on the ephod) reflects the same attention to precision-construction as the tabernacle itself.</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>You shall make a breastpiece of judgment (choshen mishpat), in skilled work:</b> Choshen = breastpiece (a pouch-like garment worn on the chest); mishpat = judgment/justice. The breastpiece of judgment is the priestly instrument for divine judicial consultation — the Urim and Thummim placed within it (v.30) allow YHWH's judgment to be communicated. The combination of the oracular function (v.30) with the representational function (twelve tribal stones, v.17-21) makes the breastpiece the most theologically dense piece of priestly equipment: the priest brings the people before YHWH's judgment while interceding for them at his heart.</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>It shall be square and doubled, a span in length and a span in breadth:</b> The square (ravi'i = fourfold/square) doubled pouch-form of the breastpiece — folded to create a pouch that holds the Urim and Thummim. The span (zeret) = the span of the hand (approximately 9 inches/23 cm). The geometric precision (square, doubled) is consistent with the tabernacle's architectural precision throughout.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>You shall set in it four rows of stones. A row of sardius, topaz, and carbuncle shall be the first row:</b> The twelve stones in four rows of three — each stone corresponding to one tribe (v.21). The exact stone identifications are among the most debated questions in biblical scholarship; ancient gem vocabularies did not map precisely onto modern mineralogical categories, and the same Hebrew word may refer to different stones in different contexts. The first row (odem = red, likely ruby or carnelian; pitdah = yellow, likely topaz or chrysolite; bareqet = green, likely emerald or malachite) uses color-differentiated stones.</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>And the second row an emerald, a sapphire, and a diamond:</b> Second row identifications: nofekh (possibly turquoise, garnet, or carbuncle); sapir (sapphire or lapis lazuli; the same stone as the heavenly pavement under YHWH's feet in 24:10; the pavement-color appears on the priest's breastpiece); yahalom (jasper, onyx, or diamond). The sapphire/lapis lazuli on the breastpiece connects the priest's vestments to the divine throne's material — the priest who stands before the heavenly sapphire throne wears that color at his heart.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>And the third row a jacinth, an agate, and an amethyst:</b> Third row: leshem (possibly hyacinth/jacinth, a yellow-red stone); shevo (possibly agate); achlamah (amethyst). The twelve-stone inventory has parallels in ancient lists of precious stones; the 'twelve-stone catalogue' tradition is found in Egyptian and Mesopotamian gem texts, though the correspondences are not exact. The Revelation 21:19-20 list of the New Jerusalem's twelve foundation stones draws on this tradition, correlating each stone to an apostle rather than a tribe.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>And the fourth row a beryl, an onyx, and a jasper. They shall be set in gold filigree:</b> Fourth row: tarshish (possibly beryl or chrysolite; the same stone as the color of Ezekiel's cherubim-wheels, Ezek 1:16); shoham (the same stone as the shoulder-pieces, onyx or sardonyx); yashfeh (jasper). All twelve stones mounted in gold filigree settings (mishbetzot zahav) — the four rows of three, the tribal colors, and the gold settings together constitute the most elaborate piece of religious jewelry described in the ancient Near East outside of Egyptian royal and divine adornment.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>There shall be twelve stones with their names according to the names of the sons of Israel. They shall be like signets, each engraved with its name, for the twelve tribes:</b> Each stone corresponds to one tribe, each engraved with the tribe's name. The twelve-stone breastpiece becomes a portable, body-worn representation of all twelve tribes — the high priest entering the Most Holy Place literally carries the entire covenant community at his chest. The priestly representation of the people before YHWH is not abstract intercession but a physically enacted embodiment.</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>For the breastpiece you shall make twisted chains like cords, of pure gold:</b> The twisted-cord gold chains (sharsherot) connecting the breastpiece to the shoulder-piece settings are distinguished from the corded chains of v.14 (avotot) — two different Hebrew terms for two different connecting chain systems. The technical precision of the chain descriptions reflects an actual manufacturing specification, not merely literary decoration.</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>And you shall make for the breastpiece two rings of gold, and put the two rings on the two edges of the breastpiece:</b> The breastpiece has four rings total: two upper rings connected by gold chains to the ephod's shoulder-settings (vv.23-25), and two lower rings connected by a blue cord to the ephod's waistband rings (vv.27-28). The multi-point attachment system ensures the breastpiece stays precisely over Aaron's heart when he moves — the structural engineering keeps the representational and oracular device in its theologically specified location (over the heart).</p>",
    "24": "<p><b>And put the two cords of gold in the two rings at the edges of the breastpiece:</b> The upper attachment system: two gold twisted chains from the breastpiece's upper rings to the gold filigree settings on the shoulder-pieces. The breastpiece is thus mechanically secured to the ephod from above by gold chains.</p>",
    "25": "<p><b>The other two ends of the two cords you shall attach to the two settings and so attach it in front to the shoulder pieces of the ephod:</b> The detailed mechanical description of the vestment-attachment system is one of the most technically specific passages in the Pentateuch. The modern analogy would be a jewelry specification sheet; the ancient Israelite reader would understand it as a manufacturing standard that guarantees exact replication across generations. The permanence of the design (reproduced exactly for each new high priest) is built into the instruction's detail.</p>",
    "26": "<p><b>You shall make two rings of gold, and put them at the two lower edges of the breastpiece, on its inside edge next to the ephod:</b> The lower rings on the breastpiece are the lower attachment points; they will be connected by blue cord to the ephod's waistband rings to prevent the breastpiece from swinging away from the ephod when the priest moves. The emphasis on preventing the breastpiece from 'swinging out' from the ephod (v.28) is practically important: a breastpiece that flapped loosely would be both undignified and potentially dangerous in the confined space of the Holy Place.</p>",
    "27": "<p><b>And you shall make two rings of gold, and attach them in front to the lower part of the two shoulder pieces of the ephod, at its seam above the skillfully woven band of the ephod:</b> The corresponding lower rings on the ephod's shoulder-pieces complete the four-point attachment system: upper rings (chains) + lower rings (blue cord) = the breastpiece is locked to the ephod at four points. The 'seam above the waistband' is the structural junction between the ephod's body and its waistband — a mechanically sound attachment point.</p>",
    "28": "<p><b>And they shall bind the breastpiece by its rings to the rings of the ephod with a lace of blue (p'til t'khelet), so that it may lie on the skillfully woven band of the ephod, and that the breastpiece shall not come loose from the ephod:</b> The blue cord (p'til t'khelet — the same blue as the priestly fringes of Num 15:38) as the lower fastening. The lower blue cord connects the four-ring system. The instruction 'that the breastpiece shall not come loose (v'lo yizzach)' — the same verb as Ps 30:6 ('nothing shall shake me') — frames the mechanical stability of the vestment in language of covenant security.</p>",
    "29": "<p><b>So Aaron shall bear the names of the sons of Israel in the breastpiece of judgment on his heart, when he goes into the Holy Place, to bring them to regular remembrance before YHWH:</b> The theological summary of the breastpiece's function: Aaron bears (nasa') the names at his heart (al-libo) when he goes before YHWH, bringing them to remembrance (l'zikaron) before YHWH. The high priest's intercession is structurally built into his vestments — he cannot remove the breastpiece and still be dressed for service; he cannot approach YHWH without simultaneously bringing Israel with him. The 'regular remembrance' (l'zikaron tamid = perpetual remembrance) makes every priestly entrance an act of covenant intercession.</p>",
    "30": "<p><b>And in the breastpiece of judgment you shall put the Urim and the Thummim, and they shall be on Aaron's heart when he goes in before YHWH. Thus Aaron shall bear the judgment of the people of Israel on his heart before YHWH regularly:</b> Urim and Thummim — the most mysterious objects in the OT priestly system. The names suggest 'lights' (urim, related to or) and 'perfections' (thummim, related to tamim = complete/blameless) or possibly 'curses' (arim) and 'innocences.' The most likely form is sacred lots (stones or dice with two sides) that provided binary yes/no answers to specific questions posed before YHWH. 1 Sam 14:41 (LXX text) describes Saul asking for Urim (guilty) or Thummim (innocent). They appear in Num 27:21, Deut 33:8, 1 Sam 28:6 (notably Saul cannot consult them, indicating they require priestly mediation). They disappear from the OT after David's time, when prophecy becomes the primary mode of divine communication.</p>",
    "31": "<p><b>You shall make the robe of the ephod (me'il ha-ephod) all of blue (t'khelet):</b> The robe under the ephod is entirely t'khelet blue — the most expensive and prestigious color in the ancient Mediterranean world. The Phoenicians (from the Greek 'Phoinos' = purple/red) built their commercial empire on the production of Murex dye (both purple argaman and blue t'khelet came from sea snails). The all-blue robe under the multi-colored ephod creates a monochromatic visual foundation for the polychromatic ephod and breastpiece above it.</p>",
    "32": "<p><b>It shall have an opening for the head in the middle of it, with a woven binding around the opening, like the opening in a garment, so that it may not tear:</b> The reinforced neck-opening (safa la-pi = a woven border/selvage around the collar opening) prevents tearing. The technical concern is practical — a garment that tears during the high priest's service would be a problem both liturgically and symbolically. The instruction to prevent tearing anticipates the significance of priestly garments being torn: Jesus's seamless tunic (John 19:23-24) not torn by soldiers, and the prohibition on the high priest tearing his garments (Lev 21:10), make the non-tearing of priestly garments a theological marker.</p>",
    "33": "<p><b>On its hem you shall make pomegranates of blue and purple and scarlet yarns, around its hem, with bells of gold (pa'amonim zahav) between them:</b> The alternating pomegranates (rimonim) and bells (pa'amonim) at the robe's hem. Pomegranates were a symbol of fruitfulness and abundance throughout the ancient Near East; they decorated Solomon's Temple columns (1 Kgs 7:18,20,42) and appear as architectural ornaments in Egyptian temples. The golden bells hung between the pomegranates produce sound when the priest moves. Bell-decoration on garments was used in Egypt and Mesopotamia, often with an apotropaic function — sounds at threshold crossings were believed to ward off malicious supernatural forces. The Hebrew explanation (v.35) is that the bells' sound ensures the priest does not die when entering YHWH's presence.</p>",
    "34": "<p><b>A golden bell and a pomegranate, a golden bell and a pomegranate, around the hem of the robe:</b> The alternating pattern (bell-pomegranate-bell-pomegranate) creates a rhythmic sonic and visual border at the robe's hem. The even alternation ensures the bells distribute their sound evenly around the priest's movement. The number of bells is not specified; later tradition (Mishnah Yoma 7:5 mentions 72 bells) supplemented the biblical instruction.</p>",
    "35": "<p><b>And it shall be on Aaron when he ministers, and its sound shall be heard when he goes into the Holy Place before YHWH, and when he comes out, so that he does not die:</b> The life-or-death consequence of the bells ('so that he does not die') is the most explicit statement in the OT about the danger of priestly entrance into YHWH's presence. The bells' sound announces the priest's approach and departure — an auditory signal that mediates the dangerous transition between the human and the divine realms. Whether the bells signal to YHWH (allowing preparation of the divine space for human approach) or to the priest (providing auditory confirmation that he is still in proper liturgical motion) is debated; both functions have ANE parallels.</p>",
    "36": "<p><b>You shall make a plate of pure gold and engrave on it, like the engraving of a signet, 'Holy to YHWH (qodesh laYHWH):'</b> The tzitz (plate/diadem/flower) of pure gold worn on the turban is the highest and most publicly visible priestly vestment — it identifies the wearer's fundamental status before YHWH and the world. Qodesh laYHWH = 'holiness belongs to YHWH' or 'holy/consecrated to YHWH'; the formula defines the high priest's identity in relation to YHWH rather than in relation to Israel. The engraving technique (pit'chei chotam = seal-engraving) makes the inscription permanent and legally binding — the high priest wears his identity as a sealed covenant document.</p>",
    "37": "<p><b>And you shall fasten it on the turban by a cord of blue. It shall be on the front of the turban:</b> The tzitz fastened with t'khelet blue cord to the front of the turban (mitznefet) — the most prominent point of the high priest's vestments, the item most visible to others approaching the tent. The blue cord connecting the golden plate to the turban links the golden declaration of holiness to the blue of heavenly/divine domain. The front (al-p'nei ha-mitznefet = on the face of the turban) placement makes the declaration 'holy to YHWH' the first thing visible when approaching the high priest.</p>",
    "38": "<p><b>It shall be on Aaron's forehead, and Aaron shall bear any guilt from the holy things that the people of Israel consecrate as their holy gifts. It shall regularly be on his forehead, that they may be accepted before YHWH:</b> The tzitz bears the iniquity (avon) of the holy things (kodashim) — defects, impurities, or inadvertent violations in the people's offerings that would otherwise make them unacceptable. The forehead-bearing of the people's cultic guilt parallels the shoulder-bearing of their names (v.12) and the heart-bearing of their judgment (v.29): the high priest's body is a living intercession map — names on his shoulders, judgment at his heart, guilt-bearing on his forehead. The regularly (tamid) qualification makes this function perpetual, not occasional.</p>",
    "39": "<p><b>You shall weave the coat (kutonet) in checker work of fine linen, and you shall make a turban of fine linen, and you shall make a sash embroidered with needlework:</b> The three remaining vestments — kutonet (tunic/coat, the base undergarment), mitznefet (turban, the head-covering), avnet (sash/girdle, the waist-binding) — complete the set of eight. The checker-work kutonet (tashbetz = checkered/woven in a mosaic pattern) is fine linen; the turban is fine linen; the sash uses the roqem embroidery technique (the same as the outer court gate screen). The regular priests (Aaron's sons) wear simpler versions of the same vestments (v.40).</p>",
    "40": "<p><b>For Aaron's sons you shall make coats and sashes and caps. You shall make them for glory and beauty:</b> The regular priests' vestments replicate Aaron's basic set (tunic, sash, headgear) at a simpler level — no ephod, no breastpiece, no tzitz, no blue robe. The same aesthetic standard (l'khavod ul'tifaret = for glory and beauty) applies to the sons' vestments as to the high priest's, maintaining the principle that all priestly service clothes must meet a quality standard befitting the divine presence.</p>",
    "41": "<p><b>And you shall put them on Aaron your brother, and on his sons with him, and shall anoint them and ordain them (male'ta et-yadam) and consecrate them, that they may serve me as priests:</b> Male'ta et-yadam = 'you shall fill their hands' — the ordination formula (literally 'filling of the hand'). The Akkadian idiom qatam malu (to fill the hand) was used in Mesopotamia for the formal investiture of someone with an office — placing in their hand the tools, symbols, or materials that defined the office. The Israelite adaptation places the sacrificial portions in the priests' hands as the symbol of their office; their hands are 'filled' with the substance of their calling. The three-stage consecration (anoint + ordain + consecrate) is then elaborated in ch.29.</p>",
    "42": "<p><b>You shall make for them linen undergarments to cover their naked flesh. They shall reach from the hips to the thighs:</b> The linen undergarments (michnesayim = breeches/linen shorts) ensure priestly modesty when ascending the altar steps. The modesty concern was already signaled in Exod 20:26 ('do not go up my altar on steps, lest your nakedness be exposed') — the linen breeches, combined with no altar-steps (the altar has its own ramp in later practice), address the modesty-at-height problem. Egyptian priests also wore linen garments as the primary fabric of priestly dress — linen's white purity was the standard priestly color across cultures in the ancient Mediterranean.</p>",
    "43": "<p><b>They shall be on Aaron and on his sons when they go into the tent of meeting or when they come near the altar to minister in the Holy Place, lest they bear guilt and die:</b> The life-or-death framework extends to the undergarments — even the garments not visible to others are subject to YHWH's standard. The 'lest they die' formula (v'lo-yis'u avon va'metu) parallels the bells formula (v.35) and the veil-barrier formula (Lev 16:2). Approaching YHWH's holiness without proper preparation is consistently lethal in the Exodus-Leviticus narrative. The undergarments are a perpetual statute (chuqqat olam) — the modesty requirement is as permanent as the atonement requirement. The vestment system as a whole creates a total-body mediation: every part of the priest is regulated when he stands before YHWH.</p>"
  },
  "29": {
    "1": "<p><b>Now this is what you shall do to them to consecrate them, that they may serve me as priests. Take one bull of the herd and two rams without blemish:</b> The ordination sacrifice ensemble: one bull (par ben-baqar = young bull of the herd) + two rams (shnei eilim) — all without blemish (t'mimim = complete/unblemished). The 'without blemish' standard (tamim from tamam = to be complete) applies to every sacrificial animal in Israel's law; defective animals cannot represent the covenant people before the perfect God. This standard has direct ANE parallels: Mesopotamian temple records specify 'perfect' animals for major offerings; the Hittite ritual texts (Hittite šuppi = pure/ritually clean) also specify unblemished sacrificial animals.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>And unleavened bread, unleavened cakes mixed with oil, and unleavened wafers smeared with oil. You shall make them of fine wheat flour:</b> Three types of unleavened grain offerings accompany the ordination sacrifices: matzot (plain unleavened loaves), challot matzot (unleavened rounds/rounds mixed with oil), and raqiqei matzot (unleavened wafers spread with oil). The three forms of unleavened bread cover the range of grain-offering presentations in the later Levitical system (Lev 2). The use of fine wheat flour (solet) — the highest quality flour — reflects the ordination's sacred significance. The absence of leaven is consistent with the Passover association: the priestly ordination is performed under the same purity-standard as the founding festival of Israel's covenant life.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>You shall put them in one basket and bring them in the basket, and bring the bull and the two rams:</b> The basket (sal) containing all three bread types is brought together with the animals — the grain and animal components of the ordination sacrifices arrive as a unified offering. This basket-and-animal presentation will be echoed in the Levitical nazirite release ceremony (Num 6:15-17) and in the leper-cleansing ceremony (Lev 14:10), both of which require the same combination of grain and animal offerings, suggesting a ritual family that includes the ordination as its founding type.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>You shall bring Aaron and his sons to the entrance of the tent of meeting and wash them with water:</b> The washing (rachatz = to wash) at the tent entrance is the first act of ordination — ritual purification before investiture with sacred garments. Egyptian priestly installation ceremonies included ritual washing; the Ptolemaic temple texts at Edfu and Dendera describe washing rites for priests entering service. The tent-entrance location (petach ohel mo'ed) is the liminal threshold that recurs for all major priestly acts; it is the boundary between the ordinary world and the sacred space.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>Then you shall take the garments, and put on Aaron the coat and the robe of the ephod, and the ephod, and the breastpiece, and gird him with the skillfully woven band of the ephod:</b> The vestition (clothing) ceremony follows the washing: the garments are put on in order from undermost (tunic/coat) to outermost (ephod with breastpiece), then belted. The dressing of the priest by another (Moses dresses Aaron) creates a ritualized hierarchy: the mediator installs the mediator. The verb labash (to clothe/dress someone else) is used in coronation contexts in the OT (Ps 109:29; Job 29:14 — 'I clothed myself with righteousness') and for YHWH clothing creation figures (Gen 3:21 — 'YHWH made garments for them').</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>And you shall set the turban on his head and put the holy crown (nezer haqodesh) on the turban:</b> The turban with the golden plate (tzitz = the holy crown/nezer) placed on top is the culmination of the vestition. Nezer = crown/dedication (the word for both the priestly diadem and the nazirite's hair-crown of dedication); the priestly nezer is the visible marker of Aaron's separation to YHWH. Egyptian coronation ceremonies involved the placement of the royal crowns on the pharaoh's head as the defining act of enthronement; the Israelite high priest's installation uses the same ceremonial structure but replaces the royal double-crown with the tzitz declaring YHWH's holiness.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>And you shall take the anointing oil and pour it on his head and anoint him:</b> The anointing of the high priest (mashiach ha-kohen = the anointed priest, Lev 4:3) with the shemen mishchah (anointing oil) is the act that constitutes him as mashiach — anointed one. The high priest joins the king as the OT's primary 'anointed' figure; both are mashiach (the later royal Messiah terminology develops from the convergence of priestly and royal anointing). In the ANE, anointing with oil was used for investiture of kings (the Amarna letters describe the oil-anointing of vassal kings by their overlords) and consecration of sacred objects and spaces.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>Then you shall bring his sons and put coats on them:</b> Aaron's sons receive the same basic vestition (coats/tunics) without the elaborate high-priestly ensemble. The son's installation as priests (kohanim) is accomplished through the same washing-dressing-anointing sequence as Aaron's, at a lower level of elaboration. The hierarchy within the priesthood (Aaron = high priest; sons = regular priests) is structurally embedded in the installation ceremony's differential richness.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>And you shall gird Aaron and his sons with sashes and bind caps on them. And the priesthood shall be theirs by a statute forever. Thus you shall ordain Aaron and his sons:</b> The caps (migba'ot = dome-shaped hats, distinct from the high priest's turban/mitznefet) complete the regular priests' vestments. 'You shall fill their hands' (maleta et-yadam = you shall ordain them) — the filling-of-the-hand formula. The 'statute forever' (chuqqat olam) makes the Aaronic priesthood a permanent covenant institution; the Zadokite priesthood that inherits this office in the monarchy period traces its legitimacy back to this installation.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>Then you shall bring the bull before the tent of meeting. Aaron and his sons shall lay their hands on the head of the bull:</b> The laying on of hands (s'michah = pressing/leaning) on the sacrificial animal's head is the act of identification-and-transfer: the offerer identifies with the animal and transfers their guilt to it. The ordination sacrifices are not brought by the people on behalf of Aaron and his sons but by Aaron and his sons themselves — the priests who will bear the people's guilt must first bear their own. The sin offering bull is for Aaron and his sons' own atonement.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>And you shall kill the bull before YHWH at the entrance of the tent of meeting:</b> The slaughter at the tent-entrance (petach ohel mo'ed) is the liminal location for the most significant ritual acts. The entrance is the threshold where the holy and ordinary worlds intersect — the most powerful acts happen at boundaries. In ANE ritual theory, thresholds were the locus of maximum supernatural intensity; threshold-rites (including sacrifice, washing, and anointing) were performed at doorways and entrances in both Egyptian and Mesopotamian religious contexts.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>And you shall take part of the blood of the bull and put it on the horns of the altar with your finger, and the rest of the blood you shall pour out at the base of the altar:</b> The blood manipulation at ordination: some blood applied to the altar's horns (the four projections at the corners), the remainder poured at the altar's base. The horns receive the blood directly; the base receives the overflow — the altar is marked top (horns) and bottom (base) with the same blood, consecrating its full extent. The blood at the base is the 'foundation pouring' attested in Mesopotamian and Egyptian temple rituals where libations were poured at the base of altars to feed or honor the deity.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>And you shall take all the fat that covers the entrails, and the long lobe of the liver, and the two kidneys with the fat that is on them, and burn them on the altar:</b> The fatty portions dedicated to YHWH: the covering fat of the entrails (chelev = the pure hard fat surrounding the organs), the liver lobe (yoteret = the caudate lobe or diaphragmatic muscle over the liver), and the kidneys with their surrounding fat. These are the same portions dedicated to YHWH in every peace offering (Lev 3) and sin offering (Lev 4). The fat belongs to YHWH (Lev 3:16 — 'all fat is YHWH's'); the burning of fat produces the most intense aroma of any burnt portion, making it the olfactory climax of the sacrifice.</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>But the flesh of the bull and its skin and its dung you shall burn with fire outside the camp. It is a sin offering:</b> The sin offering's unique disposal rule: the flesh, hide, and contents are burned outside the camp (michutz lamachaneh), not eaten. This is because the sin offering is for Aaron himself — the priest cannot eat a sin offering for his own atonement. The burning outside the camp anticipates the Day of Atonement's sin offering disposal (Lev 16:27) and, theologically, Jesus's death 'outside the gate' (Heb 13:12-13 explicitly cites this context).</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>Then you shall take one of the rams, and Aaron and his sons shall lay their hands on the head of the ram:</b> The first ram (olah = whole burnt offering) follows the sin offering (chattat). The ordering of the sacrifices — sin offering first, then burnt offering — becomes the standard sequence for the major Levitical ceremonies (Day of Atonement, Lev 16; the ordination of Israel's leadership). Atonement precedes dedication; guilt must be addressed before the total offering of self can be made.</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>And you shall kill the ram and take its blood and throw it against the sides of the altar all around:</b> The blood of the burnt offering ram is thrown (zaraq = to sprinkle/throw) against the altar's sides — not applied with the finger to the horns (as for the sin offering) but thrown in a broad gesture that covers the altar's surface. The different blood-manipulation techniques for different offerings are part of the Levitical taxonomy of sacrifice; each technique encodes a different theological meaning.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>Then you shall cut the ram into pieces and wash its entrails and its legs and put them with its pieces and its head:</b> The complete butchering and washing of the burnt offering ram before placing it on the altar — every part of the animal is used (unlike the sin offering where the inner organs are burned separately and the rest is burned outside the camp). The washing of the entrails and legs (rakhatz) removes impurities from the internal organs and the feet; the animal is presented to YHWH as clean throughout.</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>And you shall burn the whole ram on the altar. It is a burnt offering to YHWH. It is a pleasing aroma, a food offering to YHWH:</b> The first ram = the olah (whole burnt offering) consumed entirely on the altar — the most complete form of sacrifice, nothing retained for human use. Re'ach nicho'ach (pleasing aroma/soothing scent) — the formula for divine acceptance of sacrifice. The formula appears in the Gilgamesh Epic (when Utnapishtim sacrifices after the flood) and the Atrahasis Epic; in the ANE context, it described divine pleasure in the sacrifice's smell. The OT uses the formula throughout Leviticus and Numbers without the crude anthropomorphism of divine hunger, but retaining the concept of divine pleasure in the worshipper's devotion.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>You shall take the other ram, and Aaron and his sons shall lay their hands on the head of the ram:</b> The second ram = the ram of ordination (eil hamillui = the ram of filling/ordination). The three sacrifices — bull (sin offering), first ram (burnt offering), second ram (ordination offering) — create a complete ordination sequence: atonement, consecration, installation. The progression from guilt-removal to total consecration to specific installation maps the spiritual logic of all priestly service.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>Then you shall kill the ram and take some of its blood and put it on the tip of the right ear of Aaron and on the tip of the right ears of his sons, and on the thumbs of their right hands and on the great toes of their right feet, and throw the rest of the blood against the sides of the altar:</b> The whole-body anointing with blood: ear (for hearing divine commands), thumb (for doing the priestly work), big toe (for walking in the sanctuary's paths). The right side's prominence in ANE ritual is consistent — the right hand is the hand of power and blessing throughout the ancient world. The blood-anointing of body extremities is attested in the leper's cleansing ritual (Lev 14:14,17,25,28) and suggests a ritual family of 'restoration to covenant standing' that uses the same body-points. The ear+hand+foot triad creates a whole-person consecration: the priest is made holy in the faculties of perception, action, and movement.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>Then you shall take some of the blood that is on the altar, and some of the anointing oil, and sprinkle it on Aaron and his garments, and on his sons and his sons' garments with him. He and his garments shall be holy, and his sons and his sons' garments with him:</b> The final sprinkling — blood from the altar plus anointing oil sprinkled on Aaron, his sons, and all their garments simultaneously. The mixture of altar-blood and anointing oil consecrates both the persons and their vestments at once. The garments are not separate from the priests in terms of holiness — the garments are as consecrated as the wearers, and the garments consecrate subsequent wearers (v.29-30). The holiness is transmitted through the vestment-system as well as through the blood-and-oil anointing.</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>You shall also take the fat from the ram and the fat tail and the fat that covers the entrails, and the long lobe of the liver and the two kidneys with the fat that is on them, and the right thigh, for it is a ram of ordination:</b> The fat portions of the ordination ram (same as the sin offering fat list) plus the right thigh (shoq hay'mim = the right thigh) — the right thigh is the portion that belongs to the priests in the wave-offering system (v.27-28). At the ordination, Moses waves these portions before YHWH (v.24) and then burns them on the altar — Moses does at the ordination what will be the priests' role for all future wave offerings. The burning of the right thigh at the ordination is a one-time exception; thereafter the right thigh is the priest's perpetual portion.</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>And one loaf of bread and one cake of bread made with oil, and one wafer out of the basket of unleavened bread that is before YHWH:</b> One example of each of the three bread types from the ordination basket is taken for the wave offering. The one-loaf-of-each selection represents the entire basket — the portion stands for the whole, creating a ritual economy of representation that will recur throughout Leviticus (the handful of grain offering representing the whole, Lev 2:2; the firstfruits standing for all the harvest).</p>",
    "24": "<p><b>You shall put all these on the palms of Aaron and on the palms of his sons, and wave them for a wave offering before YHWH:</b> The wave offering (t'nufah): the sacrifice portions are placed on the priests' hands (palms up/together) and Moses waves them before YHWH. The 't'nufah' motion — waving/lifting before YHWH — is a cultic gesture of presentation, offering something before the divine presence as acknowledgment of YHWH's ownership. In Egyptian temple ritual, food offerings were 'presented' before the divine statue in a formalized gesture; the Israelite t'nufah is a dynamic version of the static Egyptian presentation.</p>",
    "25": "<p><b>Then you shall take them from their hands and burn them on the altar on top of the burnt offering, as a pleasing aroma before YHWH. It is a food offering to YHWH:</b> The portions waved before YHWH are taken from the priests' hands and burned on the altar — the wave-and-burn sequence at ordination enacts the total dedication that the priests will facilitate for the congregation in all future service. At every subsequent wave offering, the priests will receive their portion; at the founding ordination, the founding portion is burned entirely to YHWH.</p>",
    "26": "<p><b>And you shall take the breast of the ram of Aaron's ordination and wave it for a wave offering before YHWH, and it shall be your portion:</b> Moses receives the breast (chazeh) of the ordination ram as his officiating portion — the only priestly portion Moses ever receives (since he is not of the Aaronic priestly line). The breast is the perpetual wave-offering portion that goes to the priest in all subsequent peace offerings (Lev 7:31,34). Moses's receipt of the breast at the ordination establishes the precedent for the priests' breast-portion in all future offerings.</p>",
    "27": "<p><b>And you shall consecrate the breast of the wave offering that is waved and the thigh of the contribution that is lifted from the ram of ordination, from what was Aaron's and from what was his sons':</b> The two priestly portions — breast (chazeh hat'nufah = breast of the wave offering) and thigh (shoq hat'rumah = thigh of the contribution/heave offering) — are formally consecrated as perpetual priestly portions through the ordination ceremony. Their consecration at ordination authorizes their reception by priests for all time.</p>",
    "28": "<p><b>It shall be for Aaron and his sons as a perpetual due from the people of Israel, for it is a contribution. It shall be a contribution from the people of Israel from their peace offerings, their contribution to YHWH:</b> The perpetual ordinance (chuqqat olam) establishing the breast and thigh as the priests' portion of every peace/fellowship offering (z'vach sh'lamim). This is the economic foundation of the Aaronic priesthood's sustainability: the breast and thigh of every peace offering brought to the sanctuary provide the priests' food income. The 'contribution' (t'rumah = lifted-offering) is raised up to YHWH and then received back as the priests' portion — YHWH feeds his priests from the people's offerings.</p>",
    "29": "<p><b>The holy garments of Aaron shall be for his sons after him; they shall be anointed in them and ordained in them:</b> The high-priestly vestments pass from Aaron to his successors — each new high priest is ordained in the same garments. The garments' holiness is cumulative: each successive anointing adds to the garments' consecrated status. When Eleazar is invested with the high-priestly garments before Aaron's death on Mount Hor (Num 20:25-28), the same transfer of office through the transfer of garments takes place. The garments are the office; wearing them is being the high priest.</p>",
    "30": "<p><b>The son who succeeds him as priest, who comes into the tent of meeting to minister in the Holy Place, shall wear them seven days:</b> The seven-day period of wearing the inherited garments before taking up full service mirrors the seven-day ordination (v.35-37). The new high priest's inaugural week in his predecessor's garments is a form of consecration-by-wearing: the holiness embedded in the garments is transmitted through the seven days of use. The seven-day threshold before entering full service creates a complete cycle of preparation.</p>",
    "31": "<p><b>You shall take the ram of ordination and boil its flesh in a holy place:</b> The ordination ram's flesh is boiled (bishel = to cook/boil) in a holy place (b'maqom qadosh) — the tent entrance or the court. The cooking location's holiness requirement means the ordination meal is consumed within the sacred space, not taken outside. The physical containment of the holy food within the holy space is a form of spatial holiness management that recurs in Leviticus (Lev 6:16,26; 7:6).</p>",
    "32": "<p><b>And Aaron and his sons shall eat the flesh of the ram and the bread that is in the basket in the entrance of the tent of meeting:</b> The ordination meal: Aaron and his sons eat the flesh of the ordination ram and the basket's bread at the tent entrance. The meal within the sacred space seals the ordination covenant — the newly installed priests eat their first meal as priests within YHWH's house. Covenant meals in the ANE sealed agreements between parties; eating in the divine presence (as the elders do in 24:11) creates an especially binding covenant bond.</p>",
    "33": "<p><b>They shall eat those things with which atonement was made at their ordination and consecration, but an outsider (zar) shall not eat of them, because they are holy:</b> The ordination meal components — the atonement-bread and ordination ram — are restricted to Aaron and his sons (no stranger/outsider, zar). The holiness of the ordination food extends to its consumption; eating the holy food of ordination without ordination status would violate the sacred boundary. The zar (outsider/stranger = one without the priestly status) prohibition creates a dietary marker of priestly identity.</p>",
    "34": "<p><b>And if any of the flesh of the ordination offerings or of the bread remain until the morning, then you shall burn the remainder with fire. It shall not be eaten, because it is holy:</b> The overnight burning rule for ordination leftovers parallels the Passover rule (12:10) and the peace-offering rule (Lev 7:15): time-limited consumption prevents the holy food from becoming ordinary through prolonged availability. What is not eaten within the designated holy time is burned — it returns to YHWH rather than becoming profaned through delay.</p>",
    "35": "<p><b>Thus you shall do to Aaron and to his sons, according to all that I have commanded you. Through seven days shall you ordain them:</b> The seven-day ordination (shiv'at yamim t'male' yadam = seven days you shall fill their hands) creates a complete ordination week. The seven-day structure mirrors the creation week (seven days of divine work producing the ordered world; seven days of priestly installation producing the ordered worship system) and anticipates the Feast of Unleavened Bread (seven days), the Feast of Booths (seven days), and the mourning period (seven days). All major transitions in Israelite life are structured by seven-day cycles.</p>",
    "36": "<p><b>Every day you shall offer a bull as a sin offering for atonement. Also you shall purify the altar, when you make atonement for it, and shall anoint it to consecrate it:</b> The daily sin offering bull for seven days of ordination (seven bulls total) consecrates the altar as well as the priests. The altar must be consecrated (kipper = to atone/purify, then anoint) before it can receive the people's offerings. The dual consecration (priests + altar) in the seven ordination days creates a consecrated priestly-altar system ready to function as YHWH's interface with his people.</p>",
    "37": "<p><b>Seven days you shall make atonement for the altar and consecrate it, and the altar shall be most holy (qodesh qodashim). Whatever touches the altar shall become holy:</b> Qodesh qodashim = 'holy of holies' applied to the altar — the same phrase used for the most sacred zone of the tabernacle. The altar of burnt offering is 'most holy' in a functional sense: anything that contacts it becomes holy (yiqddash). The altar's holiness is transmitted through contact, making it a sanctity-source that consecrates what it touches. The early rabbinic discussion of how the altar's 'most holy' status interacts with individual offerings (m. Zevachim 9:1) develops this verse's principle.</p>",
    "38": "<p><b>Now this is what you shall offer on the altar: two lambs a year old day by day regularly (tamid):</b> The tamid (regular/perpetual) offering — two lambs daily, morning and evening, every day without exception — is the continuous sacrifice that defines the rhythm of Israelite temple service. Tamid = perpetual/constant (related to the root for 'always, continually'). The tamid later becomes the defining sacrifice of the Temple period, and its cessation is the signal of the Temple's destruction. Dan 9:27, 11:31, and 12:11 use the cessation of the tamid as the eschatological marker of ultimate desolation.</p>",
    "39": "<p><b>One lamb you shall offer in the morning, and the other lamb you shall offer at twilight (bein ha'arbayim):</b> Bein ha'arbayim = 'between the two evenings' — the disputed term for the time of the afternoon sacrifice (also used for the Passover lamb's slaughter in 12:6). The two-evening interpretation has generated extensive rabbinic debate: does it mean between noon and sunset (the Samaritans and Karaites), or between sunset and dark (the Pharisees)? The Passover lamb and the tamid lamb are slaughtered at the same time, structuring all Israelite sacrificial time around the two poles of morning and evening.</p>",
    "40": "<p><b>And with the first lamb a tenth measure of fine flour mingled with a fourth of a hin of beaten oil, and a fourth of a hin of wine for a drink offering:</b> The grain offering (minchah) and drink offering (nesek) accompanying each tamid lamb: 1/10 ephah of fine flour + 1/4 hin of beaten olive oil + 1/4 hin of wine. The wine poured out at the base of the altar is the drink offering — the libation that accompanies every regular sacrifice. Wine as a libation (liquid offering poured on the ground or altar) was universal in ANE sacrifice — Mesopotamian and Egyptian texts describe wine libations to various deities; the distinctive Israelite form uses wine specifically as the 'poured out' accompaniment to the tamid.</p>",
    "41": "<p><b>The other lamb you shall offer at twilight, and shall offer with it a grain offering and its drink offering, as in the morning, for a pleasing aroma, a food offering to YHWH:</b> The evening tamid mirrors the morning tamid exactly — same animals, same grain offering, same wine offering. The symmetry of morning and evening sacrifice creates a liturgical frame for the entire day: the day begins and ends in the presence of YHWH with a complete offering. The re'ach nicho'ach formula repeated for the evening offering confirms that both sacrifices are equally accepted.</p>",
    "42": "<p><b>It shall be a regular burnt offering throughout your generations at the entrance of the tent of meeting before YHWH, where I will meet with you, to speak to you there:</b> The tent entrance (petach ohel mo'ed) as the meeting place where YHWH speaks to Israel through Moses — and now, through the regular tamid sacrifice. The tamid creates a perpetual condition of openness to divine communication: the daily sacrifice at the tent entrance means Israel is always approaching YHWH, and YHWH is always available at that approach point. The meeting (mo'ed) of the 'tent of meeting' is made regular and perpetual by the tamid's daily repetition.</p>",
    "43": "<p><b>There I will meet with the people of Israel, and it shall be sanctified by my glory:</b> The tent of meeting is sanctified (niqddash) by YHWH's glory (k'vodi = my glory). The tabernacle's holiness comes from within (from YHWH's indwelling glory), not from the quality of its materials or the precision of its construction — those are necessary but not sufficient. The kavod YHWH is the true sanctifying power; the tabernacle becomes holy when YHWH inhabits it with his glory. This verse anticipates 40:34-35 when the glory fills the completed tabernacle.</p>",
    "44": "<p><b>I will consecrate the tent of meeting and the altar. Aaron also and his sons I will consecrate to serve me as priests:</b> YHWH himself consecrates (qiddashtim = I will make holy) both the structures (tent and altar) and the personnel (Aaron and his sons). Human ordination ceremonies (the seven-day installation of ch.29) are the means; divine consecration is the reality. The tabernacle and priesthood are holy not because Israel declares them so but because YHWH declares and enacts their holiness.</p>",
    "45": "<p><b>I will dwell (v'shakhanti) among the people of Israel and will be their God:</b> V'shakhanti = I will tabernacle/dwell (Qal perfect of shakan = to dwell/settle); the covenant-dwelling formula that is the theological goal of the entire Exodus narrative: YHWH will live among his people. This is the fulfillment of the burning bush promise ('I will be with you,' 3:12) and the stated purpose of the Exodus ('I will be your God and you will be my people,' 6:7). The word shakan gives its name to the mishkan (tabernacle = dwelling-place) and to the Shekinah (the rabbinic term for the divine presence dwelling with Israel).</p>",
    "46": "<p><b>And they shall know that I am YHWH their God, who brought them out of the land of Egypt that I might dwell (shekoni) among them. I am YHWH their God:</b> The da'at-YHWH formula ('they shall know that I am YHWH their God') that drove the plague narrative now becomes the stated purpose of the tabernacle and the dwelling. Egypt was supposed to know YHWH through judgment; Israel is to know YHWH through his presence dwelling among them. The Exodus from Egypt (hotze'ti otam me'eretz Mitzrayim) and the tabernacle dwelling (shekoni b'tokham) are cause and effect — YHWH brought Israel out of Egypt in order to dwell with them. The liberation was for the sake of the presence.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(existing, EXODUS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus', existing)
    print('Exodus 28-29 mkt-context commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
